Using healthy life years (HeaLYs) to assess programming needs in a public health 
unit.

Heale JD(1), Abernathy TJ, Kittle D.

Author information:
(1)Central West Health Planning Information Network, Hamilton, ON. 
jheale@cwhpin.mcmaster.ca

In December 1997, public health units in Ontario received revised mandatory 
program guidelines from the Ministry of Health in advance of the downloading of 
public health to municipalities. Public health units face difficult decisions in 
allocating municipal resources to meet the Province's mandated programs. To set 
priorities for resource allocation, it is critical to assess need across program 
areas and to use a common unit in doing so. This paper applies the Healthy Life 
Years (HeaLYs) method in assessing health need related to the mandatory programs 
for the population of Wellington and Dufferin counties in Ontario. The HeaLYs 
method incorporates duration and severity of ill-health, incidence and mortality 
in calculating years of healthy life lost (YHLL). For Wellington-Dufferin, the 
leading causes of YHLL were concentrated in the program areas of chronic 
disease, injury, and substance abuse and included four areas not addressed in 
the MPG (suicide, depression, dementia, and osteoarthritis).

